 the matrilineal and matrifocal perspectives that have emerged over the last few decades as the mother’s voice moved from silence to speech. Contributors make aesthetic, cultural, and political claims and critiques about mothering and motherhood, illuminating in new and diverse ways how authors and the protagonists of the texts “read” their own maternal identities as well as the maternal scripts of their families, cultures, and nations in their quest for self-knowledge, agency, and artistic expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aCanadian literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLittérature américainexHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aLittérature canadiennexHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aMaternité dans la littérature. 0aMother and child in literature. 0aMotherhood in literature. 0aMothers in literature. 0aMère et enfant dans la littérature. 0aMères dans la littérature. 0aÉcrits de femmes américainsxHistoire et critique. 0aÉcrits de femmes canadiensxHistoire et critique. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh1 aBeaulieu, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBode, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoulter, Myrl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula